_rawBody:
A shop sells food and drink.

\begin{parts}
\item Bananas cost \$1.20 per kilogram and apples cost \$2.25 per bag.

Work out the total cost of 3.5 kg of bananas and 2 bags of apples.

\AnswerLine[\$][]
\Marks{3}

\item Students receive a 10\% discount on their shopping.
Before the discount, the cost of a student's shopping is \$16.80.

Work out the amount of the discount.

\AnswerLine[\$][]
\Marks{1}

\item The cost of a cabbage increases by 15\%.

Calculate the new price if the original price is \$1.80.

\AnswerLine[\$][]
\Marks{2}

\item Some customers have their shopping delivered to their home.
The cost is \$5 plus \$1.50 for each kilometre travelled from the shop to their home.

\begin{subparts}
\item Show that the cost for a customer living 10 km from the shop is \$20.

\Answerspace[2cm]
\Marks{1}

\item
\begin{InsertScreenShot}
\relincludegraphics{Figures/Q02-Grid.png}
\end{InsertScreenShot}

On the grid, draw a line to show the cost of having shopping delivered.
\Marks{2}

\end{subparts}

\item A bottle of water costs \$1.55.
Suki has \$20.

Work out the maximum number of bottles Suki can buy and the change she receives.

\AnswerLine[Maximum number of bottles][\hfill Change \$]
\Marks{3}

\item A farmer delivers eggs to the shop in trays of 50.
The eggs are then put into boxes of 12.
There are no eggs left in the trays and all of the egg boxes are full.

Work out the smallest possible number of eggs that the farmer delivers.

\AnswerLine[][]
\Marks{2}

\item The shop sells bottles of orange juice in three different sizes.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ccc}
Bottle A & Bottle B & Bottle C \\
0.5 litres & 1.2 litres & 2 litres \\
\$1.30 & \$3.20 & \$5.25 \\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Work out which bottle is the best value.
Show how you decide.

\AnswerLine[Bottle][]
\Marks{3}

\end{parts}

